Template Design Pattern
The Template Method Design Pattern is a behavioral pattern that defines the skeleton of an algorithm in a base class, while allowing subclasses to override specific steps without changing the overall structure.
Itâ€™s part of the GoF (Gang of Four) patterns described in Design Patterns: Elements of Reusable Object-Oriented Software.

ğŸ“Œ When to Use It
Use Template Pattern when:
Multiple classes follow the same workflow
Some steps are common
Some steps vary
You want to avoid duplicate code
You want to enforce process order

ğŸ§  Real-World Example
Think of making tea and coffee:
Steps:
Boil water
Brew
Pour into cup
Add condiments
Boiling + pouring are same
Brewing + condiments differ
So you define the process once and allow subclasses to customize parts.

ğŸ— Structure
AbstractClass
  - templateMethod()  <-- final method (defines algorithm steps)
  - step1()
  - step2()  <-- abstract
  - step3()  <-- abstract

ğŸ”¥ Key Concepts
Concept	                  Meaning
Template Method	          Defines algorithm structure
Hooks	                  Optional overridable methods
Abstract Methods	      Steps that subclasses must implement
Final Method	          Prevents changing workflow

ğŸ’¡ Template vs Strategy (Interview Question)
Template Pattern	          Strategy Pattern
Uses inheritance	          Uses composition
Algorithm structure fixed	  Algorithm interchangeable
Compile-time behavior	      Runtime behavior

If interviewer asks:
"Why not Strategy instead of Template?"
Answer:
Template enforces workflow order. Strategy allows dynamic switching of algorithm.

ğŸ¢ Practical Usage in Enterprise Apps
In Spring Boot:
Abstract batch processing classes
Common controller workflow
Report generation frameworks
Payment processing pipelines